---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";

const ghaSnippet = `name: gode-triage

on:
  issues:
    types: [opened, labeled]

jobs:
  triage:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - uses: actions/setup-go@v5
        with: { go-version: "1.23" }
      - run: go install ./cmd/gode
      - name: Run gode
        env:
          ANTHROPIC_API_KEY: \${{ secrets.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY }}
        run: |
          gode acp --provider anthropic --auto-approve \\
            --prompt "Reproduce the failure described in issue #\${{ github.event.issue.number }} \\
                      and open a draft PR with a fix or a failing test."
      - uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
        with:
          name: gode-journal
          path: ~/.gode/sessions/`;
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Use cases"
  eyebrow="Getting started"
  description="Four ways teams put gode to work: CI automation, custom tool stacks, a plain coding agent, and as one link in a longer chain."
  prev={{ href: "/docs/install/", title: "Install & run" }}
  next={{ href: "/docs/architecture/", title: "godex harness" }}
>
  <p>
    <code>gode</code> is a coding agent and an event-driven harness, which means it slots
    into very different shapes of work. The four scenarios below are the ones we see most
    often. Each starts with the smallest invocation that works and points at the docs you
    will want next.
  </p>

  <h2>1. gode as a plain coding agent</h2>
  <p>
    The default shape. A developer opens a terminal in a repo, runs <code>gode</code>, and
    drives it through the Bubble Tea TUI. Sessions are journaled to disk, so any run can
    be resumed, searched, or replayed later.
  </p>

  <pre><code>$ gode
$ gode resume
$ gode --provider anthropic</code></pre>

  <p>This is the right starting point when you want to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Pair with a model on a feature branch without leaving the terminal.</li>
    <li>Triage a failing test or unfamiliar repo with shell, edit, search, and LSP tools available out of the box.</li>
    <li>Keep a long-running <a href="/docs/goal-mode/">goal</a> alive across sessions, with todos and subagents tracking progress.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Read next: <a href="/docs/tui/">TUI</a>, <a href="/docs/sessions/">Sessions &amp; resume</a>,
    <a href="/docs/tools/">Built-in tools</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>2. gode in GitHub Actions</h2>
  <p>
    Because gode is a single Go binary and emits a structured event stream, it runs well
    headless. Point it at a non-interactive provider, pass a prompt, and let the journal
    capture everything for the run log.
  </p>

  <pre><code>{ghaSnippet}</code></pre>

  <p>Typical CI workloads:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Reproduce an issue, attach logs, and open a draft PR.</li>
    <li>Run a refactor across a generated codebase before each release tag.</li>
    <li>Babysit flaky tests — let gode rerun, bisect, and post findings as a PR comment.</li>
    <li>Generate or update changelogs, migration notes, or SDK examples from a diff.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The <a href="/docs/event-bus/">JSONL journal</a> is the thing to keep — upload it as an
    artifact and you have a full, replayable trace of what the agent did, what tools it
    called, and which permission requests fired.
  </p>

  <h2>3. gode as part of a custom set of tooling</h2>
  <p>
    Fork the harness, keep the event bus, swap or add whatever you need. Every tool call,
    message delta, and permission request is a typed event, so plugging in a custom UI,
    exporter, or evaluator is a subscribe rather than a rewrite.
  </p>

  <p>Common shapes:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Internal IDE plugin.</strong> Run gode behind the
      <a href="/docs/app-server/">app server</a> (JSON-RPC over stdio or WebSocket) and
      let your editor drive sessions, render diffs, and approve tools.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Domain tool pack.</strong> Mount your own MCP servers via
      <a href="/docs/mcp/">stdio MCP</a> — internal search, ticketing, deploy controls —
      and they surface as <code>mcp.&lt;server&gt;.&lt;tool&gt;</code> in the registry
      alongside the built-ins.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>RL / evals.</strong> Subscribe to the event bus, write events into a replay
      buffer, score on outcomes, retrain. The harness deliberately exposes structured
      events instead of hiding them behind a CLI.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>OpenTelemetry pipeline.</strong> Tracing is wired through the runner, so
      runs show up in Jaeger or any OTLP-compatible backend with no extra glue.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <pre><code>$ gode app-server --listen ws://127.0.0.1:0
$ gode acp --provider mock --auto-approve</code></pre>

  <p>
    Read next: <a href="/docs/extensibility/">Extensibility</a>,
    <a href="/docs/event-bus/">Event bus &amp; journal</a>,
    <a href="/docs/app-server/">App server</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>4. gode in a chain of tools</h2>
  <p>
    Sometimes gode is one step in a longer pipeline — handed a prompt by an upstream agent
    or script, expected to make a focused change, and then to hand off cleanly. The
    <a href="/docs/acp/">ACP transport</a> is designed for exactly this: stdio JSON-RPC,
    no terminal, no human in the loop.
  </p>

  <pre><code>planner | gode acp --provider openai --auto-approve | reviewer | gh pr create</code></pre>

  <p>Shapes that work well:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Plan → code → review.</strong> A planning agent produces a task spec, gode
      executes it, a separate reviewer agent checks the diff before merge.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Scheduled remediation.</strong> A cron job notices drift, hands gode a
      prompt and the relevant context, gode opens a PR. The journal is the audit trail.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Sub-step in a larger agent.</strong> Treat gode as the "make the code
      changes" specialist invoked by a higher-level orchestrator that handles planning,
      memory, and approvals.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Multi-agent loops.</strong> Two or more gode instances on the same repo,
      one writing, one reviewing — both emitting to the same event bus / journal so the
      orchestrator can join the streams.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Read next: <a href="/docs/acp/">ACP guide</a>,
    <a href="/docs/providers/">Providers</a>,
    <a href="/docs/goal-mode/">Goal mode</a>.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
